The purpose of this program is to work in partnership with a range of different stakeholders to strengthen local humanitarian capability and preparedness in the Pacific and Timor-Leste so that communities are better able to respond to and recover from rapid- and slow-onset disasters.  The project seeks to ensure;  1. communities are better prepared for rapid- and slow-onset disasters, 2. the rights and needs of women, people with disabilities, youth and children are met in disaster preparedness and response at all levels,  3. government, NGOs, the private sector and communities coordinate more effectively for inclusive disaster preparedness and response, and 4. national NGOs and faith-based organisations have more influence and capacity in the country humanitarian system.

The Pacific Climate Change Collaboration Influencing and Learning project aims to develop, strengthen and maintain a working partnership between government, communities, the private sector, development partners, donors, and academic institutions on issues of climate change and disaster risk reduction in the Pacific.

Building on earlier phases of the project, this phase builds upon the achievements, evaluation recommendations and priorities of the existing partners, and is informed by the changing context and actors within the region. Implemented through the strategic partnership between Oxfam and International Rivers (IR), the project ensure target government and private sector actors at the national and regional levels engage with and include the perspectives of civil society in hydro-power and Renewable Energy (RE) policies and plans. The project also strengthens Civil Society Organisation (CSO) capacity and the leadership of women and representatives from marginalised groups to influence water governance decision making at all levels. The most recent phase incorporates activities promoting the use of alternative energy sources.

COVID19 pandemic and lockdowns that followed have disproportionately hurt marginalized communities due to loss of livelihood and lack of access to food, shelter, health, and other basic needs. This has choked off almost all-economic activities. Leading to the widespread loss of jobs and incomes for informal workers and the poor that in turn causes untold misery for them.  Oxfam's COVID-19 responses look different in each country but activities may include a) food and nutrition security covering cooked meal, dry ration and self-help community kitchens, b) water, sanitation and health (WaSH) covering bathing soaps, sanitisers, masks, sanitary napkins, disinfectants, washing powder/detergent soaps etc. for the community, c) essential health supplies for service providers (PPE kits) -full body covers, disposable googles, aprons, N95 masks, surgical gloves in additional to alcohol based hand sanitiser, handwashing liquid soap etc, d) unconditional cash transfer (UCT) as a means to give flexibility to the beneficiaries for meeting other needs over ‘fixed package in-kind support’ and as a means to boost to the local economy, e) training/ orientation of the humanitarian staff, government frontline workers on COVID19 (through digitally available mediums and using context specific methodologies that addresses the concerns of Protection Protocols for COVID19) and f) communications/materials on COVID19 in local languages

Fight Inequality Beat Poverty is a campaign and advocacy initiative. The extreme gap between rich and poor is undermining the fight against poverty, damaging economies around the globe and fuelling public anger and unrest. And that gap is growing. But we already have the tools to bridge the divide.

Close the Gap is a national campaign to raise awareness of the 10-17 year gap in life expectancy between Indigenous and non-Indigenous Australians. It aims to keep Australian Governments to account on their commitments to improve the health and life expectancy of Indigenous Australians by 2030.

Gender inequality in Sri Lanka is a major driver of poverty and injustice with women over-represented among the poor and marginalised.  Women and girls are confronted on a daily basis with norms that limit their opportunities and perceived value to society. These include physical, sexual and psychological violence. Key priorities for the Gender Justice pillar during the year 2017/18 is to develop specific target programs to addressing violence against women and GBV through developing partnership and supporting the implementation of the National Plan of Action to address SGBV  (Sexual and Gender based Violence)

In 2019, Oxfam, in partnership with technology companies Sempo and ConsenSys, successfully trialled the first delivery of blockchain-powered disaster assistance in the Pacific region through a Cash and Voucher Assistance (CVA) e-voucher system. This was done in one of the world’s most remote, and disaster-prone countries – Vanuatu.   The system runs on the Ethereum blockchain and is enabled by the participation of community-level vendors who play a direct role in micro-economic recovery and development. It is a blend of locally-led humanitarian assistance, digital financial inclusion, and blockchain innovation that combines the expertise of a leading humanitarian and development agency with an emerging Australian tech start-up company.

Following the devastating April floods in Timor Leste, Oxfam is partnering with  MANEO and the Special Administrative Region Authority of Oe-Cusse Ambeno (RAEOA) authorities to respond to the needs of persons in households led by women and/or people with disabilities. Households receive food kits (rice oil, salt, sugar and mung beans) and kitchen items (pot, frying pan, plates, spoons) so they are able to return to cook and eat in their own homes.
